'''CompCert''' is a [[Formal_verification | formally verified]] optimizing [[compiler]] for a large subset of the [[C99|C99 programming language]] which currently targets [[PowerPC]], [[ARM architecture|ARM]], [[RISC-V]],  [[x86]] and [[x86-64]]<ref>[https://github.com/AbsInt/CompCert/releases/tag/v3.0 v3.0 Release Notes]</ref> architectures.<ref>[http://compcert.inria.fr/compcert-C.html CompCert Website]</ref> This project, led by [[Xavier Leroy]], started officially in 2005, funded by the French institutes [[Agence Nationale de la Recherche|ANR]] and  [[National_Institute_for_Research_in_Computer_Science_and_Control|INRIA]]. The compiler is specified, programmed and proved in [[Coq]]. It aims to be used for programming [[ Embedded_system#Reliability | embedded systems requiring reliability]]. The performance of its generated code is often close to that of [[ GNU_Compiler_Collection | GCC ]] (version 3) at optimization level -O1, and always better than that of GCC without optimizations.<ref>[http://compcert.inria.fr/compcert-C.html#perfs CompCert Performance]</ref>

Since 2015 [[AbsInt]] offers commercial licenses, provides support and maintenance, and contributes to the advancement of the tool.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}

